This can be reduced:
```c++
vector&lt;long&gt; arr(n,0);
for(long i=0;i&lt;m;i++)
{
    for(long t=q[i][0];t&lt;=q[i][1];t++)
    {
        arr[t-1]+=q[i][2];
    }

}
```
to something like:
```c++
vector&lt;long&gt; arr(n + 1,0);  // n+1 needed because q[i][1] can be n-1
for(long i=0;i&lt;m;i++)
{
    arr[q[i][0]] += q[i][2];
    arr[q[i][1] + 1] -= q[i][2];
}
long sum = 0;
for(long i=0;i&lt;m;i++) {
    sum += arr[i];
    arr[i] = sum;
}
```
That works, because for example let `a := [0, 0, 0, 0, 0]` and you want to add 5 for elements of initial array from 2nd to 4th (not included), then you can do `a[1] += 5`, `a[3] -= 5` (`a` is `[0, 5, 0, -5, 0]`) and then calculate prefix sums on `a`, that will be how much you need to add to each element of your initial array (`[0, 5, 5, 0, 0]` in this case).

